  "prompt": "How can we prove that the square root of 2 is irrational?",
  "response": "I'll walk you through a classic proof by contradiction (reductio ad absurdum) that \u221a2 is irrational:\n\n1) Assume, for the sake of contradiction, that \u221a2 is rational.\n\n2) If \u221a2 is rational, it can be expressed as a fraction p/q in lowest terms (where p and q are integers with no common factors).\n\n3) This means: \u221a2 = p/q\n\n4) Square both sides: 2 = p\u00b2/q\u00b2\n\n5) Rearrange: 2q\u00b2 = p\u00b2\n\n6) This means p\u00b2 is even, which implies p is even.\n\n7) If p is even, let p = 2k for some integer k.\n\n8) Substitute: 2q\u00b2 = (2k)\u00b2 = 4k\u00b2\n\n9) Simplify: q\u00b2 = 2k\u00b2\n\n10) This means q\u00b2 is even, which implies q is even.\n\n11) But this contradicts our initial assumption that p/q was in lowest terms, since we've shown both p and q are even.\n\n12) Therefore, our initial assumption must be false.\n\n13) Thus, \u221a2 must be irrational.\n\nThis proof shows \u221a2 cannot be expressed as a ratio of integers.",
